      <entry corresp="til" type="particle">
        <form xml:lang="ta">til</form>
        <gramGrp>
            <gram>enclitic particle</gram>
        </gramGrp>
        <sense>
            <usg xml:lang="en">a particle expressing longing or potentiality</usg>
            <cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Kuruntokai/KT14.xml?id=KT14&amp;w=13,14">
                <q xml:lang="ta"><w>peṟuka-tillamma</w> <w>yāṉ-ē</w></q>
                <q xml:lang="en">If only I could get her!</q>
                <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Kuruntokai/KT14.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DKT14%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(3)"><title xml:lang="ta">Kuṟuntokai</title> 14, line 3</ref>
            </cit>
            <cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Purananuru/PN284.xml?id=PN284&amp;w=0,4">
                <q xml:lang="ta"><w>varuka-til</w> <w>val-<c type="geminated">l</c>ē</w> <w>varuka-til</w> <w>val</w> <w><c type="geminated">l</c>eṉa</w></q>
                <q xml:lang="en">saying, <q>please come quickly, please come quickly!</q></q>
                <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Purananuru/PN284.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DPN284%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(1)"><title xml:lang="ta">Puṟanāṉūṟu</title> 284, line 1</ref>
            </cit>
            <cit source="../Ainkurunuru/Aink204.xml?id=Aink204&amp;w=20,22">
                <q xml:lang="ta"><w>tīyēṉ-tilla</w> <w>malai</w> <w>kiḻavōṟk<c type="elided">u</c>-ē</w></q>
                <q xml:lang="en">[Why] would I be bad for the lord of the mountain?</q>
                <ref target="../Ainkurunuru/Aink204.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DAink204%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(5)"><title xml:lang="ta">Aiṅkuṟunūṟu</title> 204, line 5</ref>
            </cit>
            <note xml:lang="en">
This particle is usually enclitic with the optative in <foreign xml:lang="ta">-ka</foreign>. It may also be expanded to <foreign xml:lang="ta">tilla</foreign> or <foreign xml:lang="ta">tillamma</foreign>. The <title xml:lang="ta">Tolkāppiyam</title> states three functions that are conveyed by this particle — indicating a wish (<foreign xml:lang="ta">viḻaivu</foreign>), time (<foreign xml:lang="ta">kālam</foreign>, i.e., the contrast between the present and a desired future action), or subtext (<foreign xml:lang="ta">oḻiyicai</foreign>). It further specifies that the indication of a wish is only relevant when used with the first person. For a full discussion, see <title xml:lang="ta">Collatikāram</title> <ref target="../Tolkappiyam/TolC253.xml">253</ref> &amp; <ref target="../Tolkappiyam/TolC260.xml">260</ref>. Note, however, that the commentary on <title xml:lang="ta">Puṟanāṉūṟu</title> <ref target="../Purananuru/PN246.xml">246</ref> glosses the usage of <foreign xml:lang="ta">til</foreign> as <foreign xml:lang="ta">viḻaivu</foreign> even though it is used with the second person.
            </note>
            <note xml:lang="en">
Although not sanctioned by the <title xml:lang="ta">Tolkāppiyam</title> or its commentators, modern lexica generally class <foreign xml:lang="ta">til</foreign> as an <foreign xml:lang="ta">acaiccol</foreign>, a metrical filler.
            </note>
            <note xml:lang="en">
In a few cases, <foreign xml:lang="ta">til</foreign> can also be found in other contexts, often following an indicative first person verb form (<title xml:lang="ta">Akanāṉūṟu</title> 6) or first person pronominalised noun (<title xml:lang="ta">Aiṅkuṟunūṟu</title> 204). See also the quotations given in Rajam 1992 (420–421). Examples of this kind are comparatively rare — they are not found at all in the <title xml:lang="ta">Kuṟuntokai</title> or <title xml:lang="ta">Naṟṟiṇai</title>, nor are they cited by the <title xml:lang="ta">Tolkāppiyam</title> commentators. 

            </note>
            <note xml:lang="en">
See also the particles <foreign xml:lang="ta">maṉṟil</foreign>, <foreign xml:lang="ta">maṉṟilla</foreign>, and <foreign xml:lang="ta">āṟṟilla</foreign>.
            </note>
        </sense>
        <sense>
            <usg xml:lang="en">an interjection</usg>
            <cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Ainkurunuru/Aink319.xml?id=Aink319&amp;w=15,18">
                <q xml:lang="ta"><w>maṟantaṉar-ō</w> <w>til</w> <w>maṟavā</w> <w>nam-<c type="geminated">m</c>ē</w></q>
                <q xml:lang="en">Alas, has he forgotten us, who haven't forgotten him?</q>
                <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Ainkurunuru/Aink319.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DAink319%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(4)"><title xml:lang="ta">Aiṅkuṟunūṟu</title> 319, line 4</ref>
            </cit>
            <note xml:lang="en">
An extraordinary usage of <foreign xml:lang="ta">til</foreign> occurs in the <title xml:lang="ta">Aiṅkuṟunūṟu</title>, where it seems to be an interjection following the particle <foreign xml:lang="ta">ō</foreign> (241 &amp; 319).             </note>
        </sense>
